04986nam a22005295i 9780226196022DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20152015ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2014026046  a9780226196022  a(DE-B1597)550173  a(OCoLC)904598353  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aPR4038.L33bD66 2015 4aPR4038.L33bD66 2016 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a823.72231 aDoody, Margaret, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJane Austen's Names :bRiddles, Persons, Places /cMargaret Doody. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (472 p.) :b25 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note on Texts -- tPart I. England -- tChapter 1. Words, Names, Persons, and Places -- tChapter 2. Names as History -- tChapter 3. Civil War, Ruins, and the Conscience of the Rich -- tPart II. Names -- tChapter 4. Naming People -- tChapter 5. Titles, Status, and Surnames: Austen’s Great Surname Matrix -- tChapter 6. Personal Names (First Names and Surnames) in the “Steventon” Novels -- tChapter 7. Personal Names in the “Chawton” Novels -- tPart III. Places -- tChapter 8. Humans Making and Naming a Landscape -- tChapter 9. Placing the Places -- tChapter 10. Counties, Towns, Villages, Estates -- tChapter 11. Real and Imaginary Places in the “Chawton” Novels -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Jane Austen’s works, a name is never just a name. In fact, the names Austen gives her characters and places are as rich in subtle meaning as her prose itself. Wiltshire, for example, the home county of Catherine Morland in Northanger Abbey, is a clue that this heroine is not as stupid as she seems: according to legend, cunning Wiltshire residents caught hiding contraband in a pond capitalized on a reputation for ignorance by claiming they were digging up a “big cheese”—the moon’s reflection on the water’s surface. It worked. In Jane Austen’s Names, Margaret Doody offers a fascinating and comprehensive study of all the names of people and places—real and imaginary—in Austen’s fiction. Austen’s creative choice of names reveals not only her virtuosic talent for riddles and puns. Her names also pick up deep stories from English history, especially the various civil wars, and the blood-tinged differences that played out in the reign of Henry VIII, a period to which she often returns. Considering the major novels alongside unfinished works and juvenilia, Doody shows how Austen’s names signal class tensions as well as regional, ethnic, and religious differences. We gain a new understanding of Austen’s technique of creative anachronism, which plays with and against her skillfully deployed realism—in her books, the conflicts of the past swirl into the tensions of the present, transporting readers beyond the Regency. Full of insight and surprises for even the most devoted Janeite, Jane Austen’s Names will revolutionize how we read Austen’s fiction.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aNames in literature. 0aNames, Geographical, in literature. 0aNames, Personal, in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  anaming, austen, victorian, romanticism, satire, northanger abbey, persuasion, sense and sensibility, pride prejudice, emma, mansfield park, place names, geography, characters, riddles, puns, wordplay, character development, allusion, intertextuality, literary criticism, literature, classics, british, history, civil wars, religion, unfinished works, juvenilia, class, difference, creative anachronism, realism, regency, invasion, migration, conflict, ruins, wealth, memory, ste